7. Train a meta-classifier and note the accuracy on test data

In [174]:
from sklearn import model_selection
from mlxtend.classifier import StackingClassifier
In [175]:
clf1 = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=5)
clf2 = GaussianNB()
clf3 = SVC()
In [176]:
lr = LogisticRegression()# LogisticRegression()
In [177]:
sclf = StackingClassifier(classifiers=[clf1, clf2, clf3], meta_classifier = lr)
In [178]:
print('3-fold cross validation:\n')

for clf, label in zip([clf1, clf2, clf3, sclf], ['KNN', 'Naive Bayes','SVM',
                                                 'StackingClassifier']):
    scores = model_selection.cross_val_score(clf, X, y, cv=10, scoring='accuracy')
    print("Accuracy: %0.2f (+/- %0.2f) [%s]"  % (scores.mean(), scores.std(), label))

3-fold cross validation:

Accuracy: 0.76 (+/- 0.14) [KNN]
Accuracy: 0.70 (+/- 0.17) [Naive Bayes]
Accuracy: 0.81 (+/- 0.08) [SVM]
Accuracy: 0.80 (+/- 0.11) [StackingClassifier]

9. Compare all the models (minimum 5) and pick the best one among them

from standard classification algorithms, Support vector machines has higher accuracy compare to Logistic, KNN & Naive Bayes.

Logistic & KNN has same test accuracy,but KNN is distance based which not perfect for this situation.

The Naive Bayes giving the accuracy less in comaprision to other models meaning the probability of determing the target correctly is less.

If we look to Ensemble techniques Random Forest is better technique has higher accuary compare to Bagging & Gradient Boost.

Overall if we compare standard classification algorithms & Ensemble techniques, we can say Random forest is the best technique can be used in terms of accuracy & SVM will be second most best.
